<!-- INTRO -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="intro">
    <p>Food is more than fuel — it's medicine, culture, energy, and joy. Yet with so much conflicting advice flying around, it's easy to feel overwhelmed before you've even opened the fridge. Here's the good news: <strong>eating nutritiously doesn't have to be complicated, expensive, or boring.</strong></p>
    <p>Whether you're cooking for one, feeding a family, training for a marathon, or simply trying to feel a little better each day — this guide has something for you. Let's dive into the superfoods worth knowing, the nutrients your body actually needs, how to plan meals without losing your mind, and how to do it all without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>"Let food be thy medicine, and medicine be thy food." The ancient wisdom still holds — and modern science is proving it every day.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- SECTION 1: SUPERFOODS -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="section">
    <span class="section-badge">Superfoods</span>
    <h2>Nature's Nutritional Powerhouses</h2>
    <p>The term "superfood" gets thrown around a lot, but at its core it simply means foods that are exceptionally dense in nutrients relative to their calories. You don't need to hunt down rare Himalayan berries — some of the most powerful superfoods are already in your local supermarket.</p>

    <div class="sf-grid">
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🥦</span>
        <h4>Broccoli</h4>
        <p>Loaded with vitamin C, K, and folate. Contains sulforaphane, a compound linked to cancer prevention.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Anti-inflammatory</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🫐</span>
        <h4>Blueberries</h4>
        <p>Antioxidant kings. Protect your brain, lower blood pressure, and fight oxidative stress.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Brain health</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🐟</span>
        <h4>Salmon</h4>
        <p>Rich in omega-3 fatty acids, B vitamins, and high-quality protein. Great for heart and joints.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Heart health</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🥑</span>
        <h4>Avocado</h4>
        <p>Healthy monounsaturated fats, potassium, and fibre. Helps absorb fat-soluble vitamins.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Healthy fats</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🍠</span>
        <h4>Sweet Potato</h4>
        <p>Beta-carotene, vitamin A, and complex carbs for sustained energy. Naturally sweet and filling.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Energy</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sf-card">
        <span class="sf-icon">🌰</span>
        <h4>Walnuts</h4>
        <p>Plant-based omega-3s, magnesium, and antioxidants. A small handful goes a long way.</p>
        <span class="sf-tag">Brain &amp; heart</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Don't Overlook the Everyday Heroes</h3>
    <p>While trendy superfoods grab headlines, humble ingredients like lentils, eggs, oats, spinach, and garlic are nutritional goldmines that have sustained human health for millennia. The key isn't eating one magical food — it's building a colourful, varied diet where every meal delivers something your body loves.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- SECTION 2: NUTRIENTS -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="section">
    <span class="section-badge teal">Nutrients &amp; Vitamins</span>
    <h2>What Your Body Actually Needs</h2>
    <p>Nutrients fall into two groups: <strong>macronutrients</strong> (proteins, carbohydrates, fats) that provide energy, and <strong>micronutrients</strong> (vitamins and minerals) that keep your systems running smoothly. Here's a quick-reference guide to the ones worth paying attention to:</p>

    <table class="nutrient-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Nutrient</th>
          <th>Why it matters</th>
          <th>Best sources</th>
          <th>Note</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Protein</td>
          <td>Builds &amp; repairs muscle, makes enzymes &amp; hormones</td>
          <td>Eggs, chicken, lentils, tofu, Greek yogurt</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Macro</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Omega-3</td>
          <td>Reduces inflammation, supports brain &amp; heart</td>
          <td>Salmon, sardines, walnuts, flaxseed, chia</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Essential fat</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Fibre</td>
          <td>Feeds gut bacteria, lowers cholesterol, steadies blood sugar</td>
          <td>Oats, beans, vegetables, fruit, whole grains</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Macro</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Vitamin D</td>
          <td>Bone health, immune function, mood regulation</td>
          <td>Sunlight, fatty fish, fortified dairy, eggs</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Fat-soluble</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Iron</td>
          <td>Carries oxygen in the blood; prevents fatigue</td>
          <td>Red meat, spinach, lentils, fortified cereals</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Mineral</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Magnesium</td>
          <td>Muscle &amp; nerve function, sleep quality, energy</td>
          <td>Dark chocolate, nuts, seeds, leafy greens</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Mineral</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Vitamin C</td>
          <td>Immune support, collagen synthesis, iron absorption</td>
          <td>Bell peppers, citrus, strawberries, broccoli</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Water-soluble</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Calcium</td>
          <td>Strong bones &amp; teeth, muscle contractions, nerve signals</td>
          <td>Dairy, fortified plant milks, almonds, tofu</td>
          <td><span class="pill">Mineral</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>A Simple Rule of Thumb</h3>
    <p>If your plate is colourful, you're probably doing well. Different pigments in plants — from the orange of carotenoids to the deep purple of anthocyanins — each signal different nutrient profiles. Aim to eat the rainbow across the week, not just the brown and beige.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- MOTIVATIONAL BANNER -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="motivation-banner">
    <h2>Small Changes, Big Results</h2>
    <p>You don't need to overhaul your life overnight. Swap one processed snack for a handful of nuts. Add a vegetable to one meal a day. Drink one more glass of water. These tiny shifts compound into extraordinary health over time.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- SECTION 3: MEAL PLANNING -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="section">
    <span class="section-badge amber">Meal Planning</span>
    <h2>A Week of Nourishing Meals (Sample Plan)</h2>
    <p>The biggest barrier to eating well is usually not knowledge — it's decision fatigue. Having a loose plan at the start of the week means you're less likely to reach for takeaway on a tired Tuesday. Here's a flexible, nutritious template to inspire you:</p>

    <div class="meal-plan">
      <div class="day-card">
        <div class="day-header">Monday</div>
        <div class="meal-item">
          <div class="meal-label">Breakfast</div>
