<!-- SECTION 4: BUDGET -->
<div class="container">
  <div class="section">
    <span class="section-badge gold">Budget-Friendly Eating</span>
    <h2>Eat Like a Nutritionist Without Spending Like One</h2>
    <p>Healthy eating has a reputation for being expensive, but it doesn't have to be. Some of the most nutritious foods on the planet — eggs, lentils, oats, cabbage, canned sardines, frozen vegetables — are also among the cheapest. Here's how to make the most of your grocery budget:</p>

    <div class="tips-list">
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Embrace frozen fruits &amp; vegetables</h4>
          <p>Frozen produce is picked and frozen at peak ripeness, meaning the nutrient content is often equal to or better than "fresh" produce that's been sitting in transit for days. Stock your freezer with peas, spinach, berries, and edamame.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Build your diet around legumes</h4>
          <p>Lentils, chickpeas, kidney beans, and black beans are incredibly cheap, high in protein and fibre, and incredibly versatile. A 500g bag of dried lentils can feed a family of four several times over for just a few dollars.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Buy whole grains in bulk</h4>
          <p>Oats, brown rice, wholegrain pasta, and barley cost a fraction of processed alternatives and keep you full far longer. Buy the largest affordable bag and store in airtight containers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Plan before you shop</h4>
          <p>Impulse buying is the silent killer of grocery budgets. A 10-minute meal plan and a strict shopping list can cut your weekly spend by 20–30% while reducing food waste dramatically.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Eat seasonally and locally</h4>
          <p>Seasonal produce is fresher, tastier, and often 40–60% cheaper than out-of-season imports. Visit your local market towards closing time for great deals on produce that needs to be used soon.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-item">
        <div class="tip-num">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Master the "use-it-up" meal</h4>
          <p>Before your weekly shop, cook one meal entirely from what's left in the fridge. A stir-fry, a frittata, or a hearty soup can use up odds and ends beautifully — and this habit alone can save hundreds a year.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
